prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: Oph disks
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: Band 7 observations of young disks in Ophiuchus

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
We propose to observe 37 protoplanetary disks in the Ophiuchus star forming The observations will be acquired in the 870 micron continuum, 12CO J=3-2, and 13CO J=3-2. For the nominal weather conditions at this frequency, the program will require 6.8 hours including calibrations and overhead.
Receiver Band - - - - - - - - - - - - - The submillimeter flux scales with frequency as approximately nu^2.5 if the emission is optically thin. Considering both receive noise and atmospheric conditions, Band 7 (345 GHz) is the most sensitive of the ALMA bands to dust.
Array Configuration - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - We request a resolution of 0.13 arcsec, which can be achieved with the most extended array configuration provided for Band 7 during Cycle 2. This angular resolution resolve the disks to provide the maximum information on the presence of dust depleted cavities. The maximum angular scale that is sampled in the most extented configuation is 2.65 arcsec, which is comparable to the expected disk size but much larger than the disk region that we want to probe with the proposed observations, i.e., the planet forming within 50-100 AU.
Correlator setup - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - Since the main goal of the survey is to detect the dust continuum, we will configure the bands to 1.875 GHz bandwidth to maximize the continuum sensitivity. Band 1 and 4 are placed on the 12CO and 13CO lines respectively with 0.8 km/s resolution. This is sufficient to resolve the spectral lines, which will extend over a few km/s. The remaining two bands were placed in portions of the bands with the highest atmospheric transmission to optimize continuum sensitivity.
Sensitivity - - - - - - - - - - - We aim to detect the disk emission with a peak S/N > 10 to clearly probe the presence of small dust depleted cavities. Our simulations (see Figure 3) show that this S/N can be achieved, in the case of our fainter target, with a RMS noise level of 0.1 mJy/beam. This requires 4.75 minutes of integration on source according to the ALMA Observing Tool.
The spectral line sensitivity at this angular resolution is 5.3 K according to the ALMA sensitivity calculator. Given the 12CO and 13CO emission are optically thick and the typical temperature for the disk surface is around 50 K, this sensitivity should detect both lines.
Imaging requirements - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - The simulations shown in Figure 3 indicate that the 4.7 minute integration is sufficient to image the source with high fidelity.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: IR surveys of proto-planetary disk have revealed that transition disks are rare, only 2% at ages <1 Myr. This result is inconsistent with the large number of transition disks detected at millimeter wavelengths. While IR observations might miss several transition disks due to the high IR dust opacity, current millimeter-wave observations are incomplete and set loose constraints of the occurrence of transition disk. We propose ALMA high-angular resolution (0.13") observations of 37 disks in the young (< 1 Myr) Ophiuchus star forming region. The observations will reveal dust depleted cavities as small as 8 AU in radius and probe the origins of planetary systems on size scales corresponding to our Solar System. The proposed research as two main scientific goals: 1) measure the occurrence of dust depleted cavities in very young proto-planetary disks. This will set fundamental constraints on the processes responsible for the formation of giant planets and brown dwarfs; 2) measure the size distribution of cavities and the morphology of the outer disk, which reflect the masses and orbits of the companions that have formed within these disks.
